						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Related-developments/West-Africans-hope-to-produce-iron-tolerant-rice" title="West Africans hope to produce iron-tolerant rice" alt="link">West Africans hope to produce iron-tolerant rice</a></h2>

	
					<p>Agricultural researchers in Burkina Faso, Ghana, Guinea and Nigeria are preparing field tests on some 80 varieties of rice designed to survive - and even thrive - in the iron-rich soils of West Africa. Beginning in May, studies in three regions of each country will test the plants’ abilities to tolerate levels of iron that would kill most high-yielding rice, said Senegalese molecular biologist Khady Nani Dramé, from the African Rice Centre in Benin. Local farmers are participating in the trials. Plant breeder Alhassan Maji, from Nigeria's National Cereals Research Institute explained he would be investigating the level of iron in the test rice's leaves, the height of the rice plants and the amount of grain produced. The first results will be ready by December 2009, he said. (Source: Esther Tola, SciDev.net, 18 March 2009)</p>
							<p><span class="date">17/04/2009</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Related-developments/West-Africans-hope-to-produce-iron-tolerant-rice">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
